SUG ANNOUNCEMENT

Dear Nekedites,

Please DO NOT make any payment for the newly announced ‚Ç¶3,500 ID card fee.

It has been confirmed that:

‚Ç¶2,500 for ID cards is already included in your school fees,
And ‚Ç¶1,000 is also paid at the bursary for the same ID card.
This means students are already paying ‚Ç¶3,500 ‚Äî same as the new charge being announced.

The SUG is currently engaging the management to address this duplicate payment issue. Until this is resolved, no student should pay again.

We will keep you updated. Stay calm and united.

Signed:
His Excellency, Dist. Comr. Ekene Valentine C.
SUG President

(23BH/0314/CS) 17 RULES TO A HAPPY & SMART LIFE‚Ä¶.‚úçüèæ

1. Speak less and listen more. And when you have something to say, mean it and people will be eager to hear you talk.

2. Never argue with people on subjects like religion, politics, and controversies. You can just agree with them or ignore them and go away. If you wish to argue with them on those subjects, they will drag you to mud.

3. Think before you speak. Rushing to say something without thinking about it first can result in saying something you will regret later.

4. Be humble and polite to others. No matter how they treat you. In the future, they will regret it.

5. Control your emotions. You need to keep their emotions at the backseat while letting logic drive the car.

6. Do not reveal your next move to anyone. No one can attack what they don‚Äôt known.

7. Don't speak about yourself. Resist shifting the focus to you.

8. Always make eye contact and be confident while talking to others. Maintain eye contact for 50 percent of the time while speaking and 70% of the time while listening.

9. Don't ever try to copy someone. Be unique.

10. Do not start something you cannot offer full dedication.

11. Silence is the best answer to h. Stop feeding them with the attention they need.

12. Train yourself for the ability to come up with great opinions. Be very analytical and this will help you see things differently. Have the reasons why you do things the way you do. Be free to see things in your own unique way.

13. Don't follow the mob/crowd blindly. Always take decisions based on facts and logic. Be bold enough to choose your path.

14. Avoid the dramas of the world. When it comes to drama and manipulation, avoid it like a plague.

15. Don't hesitate to ask meaningful questions. It shows that you are paying attention as well as being interested in the conversation.

16. Don't be always available for others. Always available equals to easily abvsed.

17. Keep yourself engaged in something. Be Dynamic. Never try to remain the same and become forever revolving.

1. List four theories of leadership and discuss how an organization can benefit from any three such leadership qualities
2. ‚Å†Differentiate between internal and external communication, expatriate on any three types of internal communication types used by modern organizations
3. ‚Å†What do you understand by communication barrier? Discuss any two of the following (a) External barriers (b) Internal barriers (c) Encoding
4. ‚Å†With the appropriate model, discuss the significance of each element of the communication process Birthday Blessings dear Birthday blessings ‚ù§Ô∏è When we de write second paper U too fine .
Hbd üéÇ HBD Dear Hbday Birthday blessings babe üéÇüéàüéä Birthday blessings ASA Happy birthday Asa Nwa Na GNS we get today ? No nah social study with home economics we get Happy birthday faith üéâ Happy birthday nwaoma Happy birthday Faith üéâüéä Happy birthday Happy birthday dear I no see my picture here oo Okay sharp You don collect since na Ah do u know me Morning paper Sure! I'll provide answers to all the questions listed in your exam paper. Since you only need to answer four, you can pick the ones you prefer from these complete answers:


---

1. With an appropriate model, discuss the elements of the communication process.
Answer:
A widely accepted model is Shannon and Weaver's Communication Model, which includes the following elements:

Sender (Source): The originator of the message.

Encoder: Converts the message into signals (e.g., speech, writing).

Message: The content or information being communicated.

Channel: The medium through which the message is sent (e.g., phone, email, speech).

Noise: Any interference that distorts the message (e.g., physical noise, language barrier).

Decoder: Converts signals back into a message.

Receiver: The person who gets and interprets the message.

Feedback: The response given by the receiver to confirm the message was understood.



---

2a. What do you understand by leadership styles?
Answer:
Leadership styles refer to the approach and strategy a leader uses to direct, motivate, and manage a group of people. It influences how decisions are made, how tasks are completed, and how team members interact.

2b. Discuss in detail any four (4) leadership styles.
Answer:

1. Autocratic Leadership: The leader makes decisions without input from team members. Useful in crises but can lead to low morale.


2. Democratic Leadership: Involves team members in decision-making. Encourages collaboration and creativity.


3. Laissez-faire Leadership: Minimal interference from the leader; team members have freedom to work as they choose. Suitable for skilled and independent teams.


4. Transformational Leadership: Inspires and motivates employees to innovate and create change. Focuses on vision and growth.




---

3. Discuss any four (4) types of communication theories.
Answer:

1. Aristotle‚Äôs Model of Communication: Focuses on the speaker, message, and audience. Effective for public speaking.


2. Shannon and Weaver Model: Highlights the technical aspects, especially noise in communication.


3. Berlo‚Äôs SMCR Model: Breaks communication into Source, Message, Channel, and Receiver. Emphasizes skills and attitudes.


4. Schramm‚Äôs Model: Introduces the idea of a ‚Äúfield of experience‚Äù and feedback loop. Communication is seen as a two-way process.




---

4a. What is organizational communication?
Answer:
Organizational communication is the process through which information, ideas, and messages are exchanged within an organization to achieve goals, maintain relationships, and coordinate activities.

4b. Explain three (3) types of formal communication channels in an organization.
Answer:

1. Downward Communication: From top management to lower levels (e.g., instructions, policies).


2. Upward Communication: From subordinates to superiors (e.g., feedback, reports).


3. Horizontal Communication: Between colleagues at the same level (e.g., team discussions).




---

5a. Define conflict.
Answer:
Conflict is a disagreement or clash between individuals or groups due to differences in opinions, values, or interests.

5b. In what five (5) ways can conflict be resolved in an organization?
Answer:

1. Negotiation: Parties discuss to reach a mutually acceptable solution.


2. Mediation: A neutral third party helps resolve the conflict.


3. Compromise: Each party gives up something for the sake of agreement.


4. Collaboration: Working together to find a win-win solution.


5. Avoidance: Deliberately ignoring the conflict (may be useful in trivial issues).




---

6. Write short notes on the following:
a. Chronemics: The study of how time affects communication. For instance, being punctual or late can send non-verbal messages.
b. Kinesics: The study of body language, including facial expressions, gestures, posture, and eye contact.
c. Symposium: A formal meeting where experts present on different aspects of a topic, often followed by audience interaction.
d. Debate: A structured argument between two sides with opposing views on an issue.
e. Conference: A large gathering where individuals discuss specific topics, often involving presentations, workshops, and networking.


---

(a) Using foreach loop, print all elements of the array below:

csharp
Copy
Edit
char[] alphabet = { 'a','b','c','d','e','f','g','h','i','j','k' };
foreach (char letter in alphabet)
{
Console.WriteLine(letter);
}
(b) C# program to validate name length:

csharp
Copy
Edit
Console.Write("Enter your name: ");
string name = Console.ReadLine();

if (name.Length < 3)
{
Console.WriteLine("The name must be at least 3 characters.");
}
else if (name.Length > 50)
{
Console.WriteLine("The name must be a maximum of 50 characters.");
}
else
{
Console.WriteLine("Name looks good.");
}
QUESTION 2
(a) While loop for scores and grades of 11 students in 4 courses:

csharp
Copy
Edit
int students = 11;
int courses = 4;
int[,] scores = new int[students, courses];

int i = 0;
while (i < students)
{
int j = 0;
while (j < courses)
{
Console.Write($"Enter score for student {i + 1}, course {j + 1}: ");
scores[i, j] = int.Parse(Console.ReadLine());
j++;
}
i++;
}
(b) A class field can take four states:

Static ‚Äì Shared across all objects.

Instance ‚Äì Unique to each object.

Read-only ‚Äì Can be assigned once, usually in the constructor.

Constant ‚Äì Value cannot change after declaration.

(c) Define OOP:
Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) is a programming paradigm based on objects and classes, supporting concepts like encapsulation, inheritance, and polymorphism.

QUESTION 3
(a) C# program with array of 5 students‚Äô birth years:

csharp
Copy
Edit
int[] birthYears = { 1992, 1964, 1982, 1995, 1994 };
int currentYear = DateTime.Now.Year;

for (int i = 0; i < birthYears.Length; i++)
{
int age = currentYear - birthYears[i];
Console.WriteLine($"Student {i + 1} is {age} years old.");
}
(b) Split string:

csharp
Copy
Edit
string names = "Sunday, Prince, Emeka, Ifeoma";
string[] splitNames = names.Split(", ");
foreach (string name in splitNames)
{
Console.WriteLine(name);
}
(c) List of 10 usernames and remove one:

csharp
Copy
Edit
List<string> users = new List<string> { "John", "Jane", "Mark", "Grace", "Luke", "Paul", "Anna", "Tina", "Max", "Hope" };
users.Remove("Mark");
QUESTION 4
(a) Instantiate object in staff class:

csharp
Copy
Edit
Staff staff1 = new Staff("John");
(b) Book class with constructor:

csharp
Copy
Edit
class Book
{
public string Title;
public string Author;
public int Pages;
public string BookName;

public Book(string title, string author, int pages, string bookName)
{
Title = title;
Author = author;
Pages = pages;
BookName = bookName;
}
}
(c) Create string array with 6 elements:

csharp
Copy
Edit
string[] colors = new string[6] { "Red", "Blue", "Green", "Yellow", "Purple", "Orange" };
QUESTION 5
(a) Program with VIP and Normal membership classes:

csharp
Copy
Edit
class Member
{
public string Name;
public virtual void DisplayType() => Console.WriteLine("Normal Member");
}

class VIPMember : Member
{
public override void DisplayType() => Console.WriteLine("VIP Member");
}
(b) Main method and object instantiation:

csharp
Copy
Edit
static void Main(string[] args)
{
VIPMember vip = new VIPMember();
vip.DisplayType();
}
QUESTION 6
(a) Statement similar to if: switch

csharp
Copy
Edit
char grade = char.Parse(Console.ReadLine());
switch (grade)
{
case 'A': Console.WriteLine("Excellent"); break;
case 'B': Console.WriteLine("Very Good"); break;
case 'C': Console.WriteLine("Good"); break;
case 'D': Console.WriteLine("Fair"); break;
case 'E': Console.WriteLine("Poor"); break;
default: Console.WriteLine("Invalid Grade"); break;
}
(b) Correcting errors:

csharp
Copy
Edit
int NOBLE = 50;
float hours = 60.5f;

QUESTION 7
(a) Array copy statement:

csharp
Copy
Edit
int[] source = { 13, 7, 1, 5 };
int[] destination = new int[4];
Array.Copy(source, destination, source.Length);
(b) Check if a number is prime:

csharp
Copy
Edit
Console.Write("Enter a number: ");
int num = int.Parse(Console.ReadLine());
bool isPrime = true;

if (num <= 1)
isPrime = false;
else
{
for (int i = 2; i <= Math.Sqrt(num); i++)
{
if (num % i == 0)
{
isPrime = false;
break;
}
}
}

Console.WriteLine(isPrime ? "Prime number" : "Not a prime number"); All of this only 4 marks ? Wednesday Bro Nigerian Military Direct Short Service Course (DSSC) Recruitment Guide

Are you a patriotic Nigerian graduate with a passion to serve your country in a professional capacity? The Nigerian Army, Navy, and Air Force are now recruiting qualified candidates into the Direct Short Service Course (DSSC).

1. Nigerian Army DSSC

1. Training Duration: 6 to 9 months
2. Age: 20‚Äì30 years (up to 35 for medical consultants)
3. Qualification: Bachelor's Degree or HND in relevant fields
4. Minimum CGPA: 2.2 (Second Class Lower) or Lower Credit for HND holders
5. NYSC discharge or exemption certificate is compulsory
6. Apply via: recruitment.army.mil.ng

2. Nigerian Navy DSSC

1.Training Duration: 6 to 9 months
2. Age: 22‚Äì28 years (Medical consultants can be older)
3. Qualification: Bachelor's Degree or HND in relevant disciplines
4. Minimum CGPA: 2.2 or Lower Credit for HND
5. Must possess NYSC certificate
6.Apply via: joinnigeriannavy.com

3. Nigerian Air Force DSSC

1. Training Duration: 6 months
2. Age: 22‚Äì30 years (Doctors: up to 35 years)
3. Qualification: Degree or HND in approved fields
4. Minimum CGPA: 2.2 or Lower Credit for HND
5. NYSC certificate required
Apply via: nafrecruitment.airforce.mil.ng

General Requirements

1. Nigerian by birth
2. Physically and medically fit
3. Minimum height: 1.68m (male), 1.65m (female)
4. No criminal record or membership of any cult or secret society

That the female lions can live up to 16 years; while the male lions live up to 10 years.

The list below are some more:

Cat- 23 years

Snakes- 30 years

Dog- 18 years

Horse- 60 years.

Elephant- 70 years

Pig - 20 years

Camel- 40 years

Goat- 18years

Tiger- 25years

Leopard-24years

Shark- 500 years

Crocodile- 45years

Cow- 22years

Parrot- 80years

Ant- 1.5 years  & ant queen- 3 years

Frog-10 years

Tortoise - 255 years

Wolf- 23 years

Hippopotamus-50years

Monkeys- 40years

Rabbit- 15 years

Did you also notice that a RABBIT runs, jumps, moves faster and lives for only 15 years, while TORTOISE doesn't even attempt any of such activities, but lives for about 250 years or more.

Life is not about rushing, comparison and doing what others are doing.

Life is about keeping calm and doing what is right and what you are called to do.

Rabbit and tortoise may live in the same forest and play together, they have different life expectancies.
Remember that you have:

Age Mates
Class Mates
School Mates
Office Mates
but you don't have
DESTINY MATE

Be who you are called to be and don't try to be somebody else.

1. *ADULT* has 5 letters,
so does *YOUTH*.

2. *PERMANENT* has 9 letters,
so does *TEMPORARY*.

3. *GOOD* has 4 letters,
so does *EVIL*.

4. *BLACK* has 5 letters,
so does *WHITE*.

5. *CHURCH* has 6 letters,
so does *MOSQUE*.

6. *BIBLE* has 5 letters,
so does *QUR'AN*.

7. *LIFE* has 4 letters,
so does *DEAD*.

8. *HATE* has 4 letters,
so does *LOVE*.

9. *ENEMIES* has 7 letters,
so does *FRIENDS*.

10. *LYING* has 5 letters,
so does *TRUTH*.

11. *HURT* has 4 letters,
so does *HEAL*.

12. *NEGATIVE* has 8 letters,
so does *POSITIVE*.

13. *FAILURE* has 7 letters,
so does *SUCCESS*.

14. *BELOW* has 5 letters,
so does *ABOVE*.

15. *CRY* has 3 letters,
so does *JOY*.

16. *ANGER* has 5 letters,
so does *HAPPY*.

17. *RIGHT* has 5 letters,
so does *WRONG*.

18. *RICH* has 4 letters,
so does *POOR*.

19. *FAIL* has 4 letters,
so does *PASS*.

20. *KNOWLEDGE* has 9 letters,
so does *IGNORANCE*.

Are they all by *Coincidence?*

This means *LIFE* is like  a double edged sword but the choice we make determines our future.

*‚ÄúI LOVE THIS ANALOGY"*.

- When *GOD*  wanted to create  *FISH*, He spoke to the *SEA*.

- When *GOD*  wanted to create *TREES*, He spoke to the *EARTH*.

- But when *GOD*  wanted to create  *MAN*, He turned to *HIMSELF*.

- So *GOD* said:
*"Let Us make man in Our image and likeness"*.

Note:
- If you take a *fish* out of the *water*
it will *die*;
And when you remove a *tree* from the *ground*, it also *dies*.

- Similarly, when *man* disconnects from *GOD*, he *dies*.

üîÜ *GOD* is our *natural environment*.
We were created to  *live in HIS presence*.

üîÜ We have to be connected to  *Him*  because only with  *Him* does LIFE exist.

- Let's stay *connected to GOD*.

üîÜ Remember that *water* without *fish* is still *water,* but  *fish* without water is *nothing*.

üîÜThe *soil* *without* the *tree* is still *soil,* but the  *tree* without soil is *nothing*.

üîÜ *God* *without* *man* is still *God,* but *man* *without GOD* is *nothing*.

üîÜ If this message reaches you and you share it with others,  that is called:

My name is James Babalola. I am an alumnus of Babcock University, studied CIS.
I run a coding school in the city of Lagos called  *The Code Center*  where we teach people how to code & design, helping them develop a successful career in it. Over the years, a great number of students from the SCSE, Babcock University (and of course, other institutions) have passed through us at The Code Center, most of who are now doing extremely well in their tech career both at home and abroad.

As summer holiday is approaching for you guys, I'm reaching out to let you all know that if you are interested, you can sign-up for our coding/design bootcamp to equip you with skills that would prepare you for SIWES ahead. Because you guys have 4months holiday to spend, we have designed/carved out the following possible programs for the interested ones among you to choose from. Below is a PDF that contains selected testimonials from just 10 people among several, who are testaments to the value you are guaranteed to get from us. Please take time to read the testimonials If you are not resident in Lagos or you are limited by distance but you would still like to participate, we have an hostel accommodation that's just about 20mins walk to our office; tho we have very limited space right now because of our SIWES students in training. However this comes at its own cost.
Also, we have provision for virtual classes if distance is a barrier for you and you don't want to explore the hostel option

Let me also hint you ahead that *you can do your SIWES at The Code Center by applying for our training programs.* Again, it is for those who are interested. I believe you all know that the 300L people are currently on SIWES - *we have about 22 people at our place who applied for our training program as their SIWES*. I will share more information about this later on I will pause here for now. Would share more information later on.
Please feel free to DM for further enquiry

At the end of June 2024, we discharged about 24 students from The School of Computer and Engineering Studies, Babcock University - who came for SIWES at our organization by applying for our training programs - meaning that they paid to learn/acquire knowledge from us.

As they were about rounding off, we requested from them a testimonial of what their experience had been like. In the PDF below, we curated the responses we got from some of them. *Please do me a favour of reading through the document* üôè People have come in contact with us at The Code Center and they have been able to find directions for their lives/career. And we just want to be able to make this happen for as many of you as possible. *It will cost you money, no doubt. But it's surely going to be an amazing/transformative/worthwhile experience for you.*
So, if you are interested, then start getting ready to make it a date with us from next year January, 2025

I will share more details with you guys before resumption. In the mean time, feel free to reach out to me for further enquiries.

Cheers to everyone.

James Babalola,
An alumnus of Babcock University & Co-founder of The Code Center

1: Some of your 400L courses such as Software Engineering, Database Management, Web Design, Internet Technologies, etc would be a walk-over for you.

2: You stand a great chance of being able to build your final year software project by yourself

3: Depending on how entrepreneurial you are and how well you can manage your time, you'll be able to handle some of your colleagues' final year project and charge them for it

4: putting 2 and 3 above together, coupled with the projects you must have worked on while on SIWES at The Code Center, you stand a great chance of landing employment upon graduation from the University You can find some of our other programs in here.
